343 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DAVIS MOVES TO HALT TAX ON OVERSEAS PURCHASES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
State Controller Gray Davis vowed Monday to seek either legislative or 
administrative action to stop the Board of Equalization from taxing California 
residents for purchases they made abroad last year. 
</P>
<P>
Davis said it was "fundamentally unfair" for state administrators not to give 
taxpayers any notice before they began charging a use tax on goods purchased 
overseas. 
</P>
<P>
"Everyone understands that hitting someone with an unexpected tax bill when 
they return from overseas is just not part of the American way," Davis said. 
"Fairness is a fundamental aspect of the American legal system. Notice is a 
fundamental aspect of the American legal system. This retroactive tax bill has 
neither." 
</P>
<P>
Board of Equalization officials said they decided to enforce the tax after the 
U.S. Customs Service agreed to give them access to the declarations that 
California residents make of their overseas purchases as they re-enter the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
Thousands of California residents began receiving the unexpected tax notices 
last week. By the end of the year, officials estimate that as many as 58,000 
travelers will be required to pay the tax. Officials acknowledged that they did 
not send out notices advising taxpayers that the levy was being enforced until 
December. 
</P>
<P>
The use tax, which was passed in 1935, applies to all goods purchased outside 
the state for use in California. However, until officials reached the agreement 
with the Customs Service, they said they had no way of enforcing it on 
purchases made overseas. 
</P>
<P>
"In effect this is really a new law," said Davis. "It's been ignored for 55 
years, so no taxpayer could be faulted for being ignorant of it." 
</P>
<P>
Davis, who is also a member of the Board of Equalization, said he will ask 
lawmakers to pass an urgency bill that would delay enforcement of the tax until 
the public can be informed. If legislation is not successful, he said he will 
ask the five-member board to delay enforcement of the tax. 
</P>
<P>
At least one board member, Chairman Conway Collis, has already suggested 
similar action by the board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
DAVIS, GRAY; CALIFORNIA -- TAXES; CALIFORNIA BOARD OF EQUALIZATION; CUSTOMS 
SERVICE (U.S.); IMPORT FEES; CALIFORNIA -- LAWS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
