<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
FLORIDA TAX DIRECTOR SUSPENDED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TALLAHASSEE, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Florida's revenue director was suspended today on suspicion of having a 
businessman's taxes investigated for political reasons. 
</P>
<P>
Gov. Bob Martinez and his Cabinet suspended Katie Tucker for 10 days with pay 
to allow her to explain her role in the Revenue Department probe of businesses 
owned by Donald G. Resha, a political opponent of her husband. 
</P>
<P>
Resha unsuccessfully ran against Tucker's husband, Daniel Miller, for president 
of the state AFL-CIO in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
Resha's bookstore and two video stores were subjected to a five-month 
investigation into allegations of pornography and sales tax violations. 
</P>
<P>
The probe found no wrongdoing, but the businesses were then audited. The audit 
found that Resha owed $588.18 in taxes, penalties and interest, which he paid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
